commit.message:
Merge pull request #4 from philippmayrth/master

Made it work on OS X v10.10

Made it work on OS X v10.10

On OS X v10.10 the _uptime_bsd() function failed to calculate the size
of the buffer and returned None
Updated documentation URL.

__main__ -b updated for datetime.

Fixes issue #2. On platforms with datetime, an exception will still be
raised, but that's alright; at least it will be descriptive.
Version bump for boottime's new return type.

More graceful handling of missing datetime.

So I remembered why boottime originally returned a time.struct_time
object instead of a datetime.datetime one (issue #1): Plan 9's most
readily available Python is so old it doesn't yet have the datetime
module.

We officially definitely don't support Python 2.2, but I'd really like
to keep Plan 9 support. There's talk of a 2.7 port, but I'm not sure
that's ready yet. So.
No more bare except blocks.

Merge pull request #1 from Riamse/master

time.struct_time -> datetime.datetime
datetime is more Pythonic, and has more stuff
Version bump.

Made _uptime_minix a separate function.

MINIX deserves better than to stand forever in Linux's shadow.
Document _uptime_mac.

Added classic Mac OS support.

Should also work for OS X, though TickCount, which MacOS.GetTicks uses,
has been deprecated since v10.8. I'll test it later.

The MacOS module was removed in Python 3, but I'm not aware of any
versions of that being available for OS 9 and earlier anyway.
Test for the equality guaranteed in the docs.
Caveat.

_uptime_posix also works on OpenIndiana.

That took forever to get working. Solaris is slow as balls.
_uptime_syllable should set __boottime.
Version bump.
Document Syllable support.

Added Syllable support.

I honestly don't know how robust this is, but I'm fucking happy with it.
Documentation tweak.

Tested on MINIX.

MINIX, it turns out, has a /proc/uptime. It contains only one number (the
actual uptime) as opposed to Linux's two (uptime and idle time), but that
doesn't break anything.
Version bump.

Added RISC OS support.

RISC OS builds of Python come with a swi module. Who knew?
Documentation is absurdly poor, but I managed. It works even with the
unofficial 2.7 port that guy did for the Raspberry Pi.

Tested on ReactOS.

ReactOS lies about what operating system it is, but it works.

Version bump.

I don't know if this should be minor or maintenance. I guess it's not
that important.
Document package-as-a-script behaviour.
Display boot time according to locale.

Should be a class method.

Apparently this doesn't matter for Python 2.6.6 or 3.1.3, but it is
necessary for 2.7.3. It makes conceptual sense, obviously; I don't know
why those versions didn't break.
Did some poking on FreeDOS.
